                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>
                                <origPlace>
                                    <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100104">Germany</placeName>
                                    <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100311">Bavaria</placeName>
                                </origPlace>, <origDate notAfter="1025" notBefore="0975">1000, circa</origDate>. Hoffmann argues <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100367">Kempten</placeName> as place of origin based on the inclusion of Sts Gordianus and Epimachus in the litany (<locus from="180r" to="180r" scheme="folios"/>) and the dating based on the inclusion of St Ulrich in the calendar and litany (<locus from="1v" to="1v" scheme="folios"/> and <locus from="180r" to="180r" scheme="folios"/>), cf. <bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107559">Hoffmann (2004)</title>
                                    <citedRange from="163" to="163" unit="page"/>
                                </bibl>.</p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>According to <bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107560">Tüchle (1978)</title>
                                    <citedRange from="198" to="199" unit="page"/>
                                </bibl> the manuscript belonged to the abby in <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100214">Thierhaupten</placeName>during the <date from="1101" to="1200">12th century</date> and after <date when="1342"/> it was transferred to the church in <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100368">Weihern</placeName>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>The manuscript is listed in Vossius's catalogue from 1651 (U 202:1, p. 15). </p>
                            <p>The signa on the spine refer to the catalogue of 1734 (U 125e): <quote>N<hi rend="super">o</hi> 16</quote>; and Hammarsköld's catalogue from the 19th century: <quote>e. 30. 6. 9.</quote>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>Taken as spoils of war during the Thirty Year's War.</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
