                                    </extent>
                                    <condition>Parchment of notably varying thickness, worn and in places, especially in the beginning, stained. The blind ruling has cut through the leaves in places, e.g. <locus from="161" to="161" scheme="folios"/> (second line from the bottom), Several holes in the leaves, e.g. on <locus from="63" to="63" scheme="folios"/>, but no loss of text. Text, mainly rubrics, faded in places, e.g. on <locus from="4v" to="5r" scheme="folios"/>. Several leaves have had strips cut from them, e.g. <locus from="273" to="273" scheme="folios"/>, but seeminly without loss of text. <locus from="1r" to="1r" scheme="folios"/>: text faded and stained. <locus from="10r" to="10r" scheme="folios"/>: leaf repaired in the upper corner.</condition>
                                </supportDesc>
                                <layoutDesc>
                                    <layout columns="1" ruledLines="19 25">
                                        <dimensions type="written">
                                            <height quantity="195" unit="mm"/>
                                            <width quantity="155" unit="mm"/>
                                        </dimensions>
                                        <note>Blind ruling. Pricking in margins.</note>
                                    </layout>
                                </layoutDesc>
                            </objectDesc>
                            <handDesc>
                                <handNote xml:id="hand-1">Carolingian minuscule. <bibl>
                                        <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107559">Hoffmann (2004)</title>
                                        <citedRange from="163" to="163" unit="page"/>
                                    </bibl> gives a description of the script and identifes a second hand on <locus from="18v" to="18v" scheme="folios"/>, lines 1-5. Furthermore, on the same page Hoffman identifies addition in the text by 12 different hands from the 11th and 12th centuries. <locus from="4r" to="4r" scheme="folios"/>, <locus from="10r" to="10r" scheme="folios"/>, <locus from="10v" to="10v" scheme="folios"/>: Hand C (Hand A and B reported as main scribal hands); <locus from="5v" to="5v" scheme="folios"/>, <locus from="6r" to="6r" scheme="folios"/>: Hand D; <locus from="6r" to="6r" scheme="folios"/>: Hand E; <locus from="7r" to="7r" scheme="folios"/>: Hand F; <locus from="9v" to="9v" scheme="folios"/>: Hand G; <locus from="10v" to="10v" scheme="folios"/>, <locus from="11r" to="11r" scheme="folios"/>: Hand H; <locus from="202r" to="202r" scheme="folios"/>: Hand I; <locus from="202r" to="202r" scheme="folios"/>: Hand J; <locus from="237r" to="237r" scheme="folios"/>: Hand
                                    K; <locus from="305v" to="305v" scheme="folios"/>: Hand L; <locus from="308r" to="309v" scheme="folios"/>: Hand M; <locus from="309v" to="309v" scheme="folios"/>: Hand N. </handNote>
                            </handDesc>
                            <additions>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="2r" to="2r" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <note>Top left corner, in ink by an early modern hand: <quote>Antiphona</quote> (this note is also found on <locus from="4r" to="4r" scheme="folios"/>).</note>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="1r" to="372v" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <note>There are numerous additions in the manuscript both by contemporary hands and later medieval hands. Additions by contemporary hands are spread out through most of the manuscripts, both interlinear and in the margins, e.g. on <locus from="295v" to="295v" scheme="folios"/>: in black in the text or between lines; <locus from="302v" to="303r" scheme="folios"/>, <locus from="326v" to="327r" scheme="folios"/>: in the top margin; <locus from="320rv" to="320rv" scheme="folios"/>: correction between the lines and in the margins; Example of additions by later hands are found on: <locus from="2r" to="2r" scheme="folios"/> additionin the marigin by a 14th century hand, notes from the dedication of the church in Weihern 1342); <locus from="3v" to="3v" scheme="folios"/>, <locus from="5r" to="5r" scheme="folios"/>, <locus from="15r" to="15r" scheme="folios"/> longer additions in the margins; <locus from="331v" to="332v" scheme="folios"/>: erasure and
                                        additions by a later hand.</note>
                                </p>
                            </additions>
                            <decoDesc>
                                <p>Main text in brown ink, rubrics in red, capitals in red in some places.</p>
                                <decoNote type="initials">
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="6v" to="6v" scheme="folios"/>: UD (Vere dignum). The monogram is outlined in red ink and has a cross at its centre surrounded by vine-stems. The mongram is enclosed in a simple frame in brown ink. This part of the page is faded, which makes the motif somewhat difficult to discern.</p>
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="7r" to="7r" scheme="folios"/>: TE IGITVR.The entire phrase is made into a monogram with the T in the centre and the other letters on each side. The R is not filled in and barely visible. The letters are intertwined with vine-stems.</p>
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="11r" to="11r" scheme="folios"/>: decorated initial H over 6 lines. The leter is painted in red, green and blue, and decorated with vine-stems. Below, the abbreviation for <quote>deus</quote> is painted in the same style, with the D over 9 lines, an abbreviation line, and an S over 3 lines.</p>
                                    <p/>
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="11v" to="11v" scheme="folios"/>: decorated initial P over 10 lines. The inital is outlined in red and deocrated with vine-stems. Some of the counterspace is filled in with a purplish blue. The leter is enclosed in a frame, which is red on three sides, and gold and green on the fourth side.</p>
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="11r" to="18v" scheme="folios"/> (24-26 Dec.), <locus from="65v" to="65v" scheme="folios"/> (Quadragesima), <locus from="125r" to="125r" scheme="folios"/> (Palm Sunday), <locus from="161r" to="161r" scheme="folios"/> (Exultet), <locus from="162v" to="162v" scheme="folios"/> (Orationes), <locus from="174v" to="174v" scheme="folios"/> (Benedictio salis), <locus from="184r" to="184r" scheme="folios"/> (Holy Saturday), <locus from="185v" to="185v" scheme="folios"/> (Easter Sunday), and <locus from="334r" to="334r" scheme="folios"/> (Pentecost): decorated initials over 3 lines (and extending below the line). The initials are outlined in red and decorated with penwork details and foliage ornaments. Counterspace or background often in a purplish blue.</p>
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="6r" to="372v" scheme="folios"/>: plain initials over 1-3 lines in red.</p>
                                </decoNote>
                                <decoNote type="images">
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="7v" to="7v" scheme="folios"/>: Full-page miniature of the Crucifixion. The motif is outlined in dark ink and coloured with touches of red and gold. The cross has a second crossbar or plaque on top. Beneath Christ's feet stand a chalice/the grail. The motif is surrounded by a thin double frame, the outer frame in gold and the inner in red.</p>
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="9r" to="9r" scheme="folios"/>: Two half-page minatures of Christ and a priest. The motifs are outlined in dark ink and coloured with touches of red and gold. To the left a priest portrayed as standing, holding or presenting a chalice. He is wearing a full-length robe, stole and has bare head. The priest is standing inside an arch. To the right, Christ is portrayed as seated on a throne, in one hand holding a book and the other hand extended in benediction. Christ's head is surrounded by a cruciform halo. The throne feature zoomorphic details.The motif is surrouded by a double-framed lozenge or rhombic mandorla.</p>
                                </decoNote>
                            </decoDesc>
                        </physDesc>
